  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a real, tangible barrier that affects how people engage with science and technology. As someone who grew up in a family where my father had only completed primary school and my mother upper secondary, I've seen firsthand how expectations can shape a child's confidence. When I was in school, teachers would often say, 'You're not good at math,' even when I was struggling with the basics. That kind of feedback, whether from teachers or peers, can create a self-fulfilling prophecy where someone starts to believe they're not capable in a field that's often perceived as 'for boys.' In STEM, stereotype threat manifests when people feel their identity—like being a woman or from a minority group—is at risk because of their performance. For example, a girl might freeze during a coding test because she's worried she'll prove the stereotype that women aren't good at tech. I've seen this in my own life as a barista in Milan; customers often assume I can't understand complex tech topics, even though I've been learning about it through hobbies like gardening and running (which involve data analysis). The good news is, addressing stereotype threat isn't about fixing people—it's about creating environments where everyone feels safe to try. This means teachers and employers should focus on inclusive language, mentorship programs, and celebrating diverse contributions to STEM. I believe we need to shift the narrative from 'you're not cut out for this' to 'you belong here.' It's not about changing who we are, but about changing how we're perceived. After all, in a city like Milan, where creativity and innovation thrive, everyone deserves to feel they can contribute without fear.",
